Marines among the 6,000 people who have laid wreaths on the graves of Arlington
The Obergefreite De ' Angello Robinson, 19, traveled seven hours by bus to lay a single wreath at the grave of a soldier who had never met.
For him and the other Marines who made the journey from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina at the National Cemetery in Arlington to decorate graves, was a day to pay tribute to the men and women who were in their place.
In a few months, from where we are embarking, these could be us, said Robinson about the fallen soldiers.
If we, I would like to see someone do the same for me, so I try to show respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who had gathered on Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington cemetery.
In 1992, Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, launched the event when he and others have decided to decorate several hundreds of graves in the cemetery in Arlington.
Now, to continue a tradition of 18 years, Morrill and his wife Karen, each year the trip, stopping in various cities along the way, to organize commemorations in honour of military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcester also founded a non - profit organization, Wreaths Across America (placed wreaths Across America) , which has extended the event to other states.
This year more than 16,000 placed wreaths on the graves of the Arlington cemetery, around the Pentagon, on the graves of the cemetery Fayetteville National Cemetery enArkansas, in Battery Park in New York City and on the site of the memorial to the victims of United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second year, the Walmart Foundation has donated more than $150,000 to buy and transport the crowns.
Charleen Hunt, 70, of Westminster, said that she had made the trip to Arlington in honour of her husband, a career soldier died.
While her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said that this was a way to thank those who made sacrifices.
This is a small gesture that civilians can do to support our troops, she said.
It is like visiting a family tomb.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, volunteers walked through the vast meadows and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers have chosen old graves dating from the First and second world war and the Vietnam War, because they are not as often as the new graves, the organisers.
The mood was optimistic, while the children played and couples were taken by the hand, while wearing the fresh pine to the sepulcrales.
Each table had a dark green, with a small red ribbon tied at the top.
Close, the Section 60, where most of the veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried.
The United Service Organizations has given 1,000 kroner to decorate the section but the gloomy mood of the current wars filled the area.
People wept openly, others prayed and families and friends supported each other in the cold air.
Some read aloud the names carved in stone, while others were inclined to see small black and white, information in the wetland for those whose tombstones have not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers in tears on the grave of her son.
It is 8 hours of Zanesfield, Ohio, to visit the tomb of the Marine. David Shane Spicer, who died in combat in July.
No one should never forget why we are free ... my son has paid for it, she said.
" long after I am gone, I want someone to remember him. "
A US citizen arrested by the Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a contractor for the U. S. government, sold the cell phones and computers in the country, said the services of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
The contractor, which has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for clients such as the U. S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
The consular authorities and the U. S. Interest Section in Havana are seeking access to the detainee, who was arrested on 5 December.
The specific charges have not been made public, although under the Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested under the pretext of being " dangerous ".
All the so - called counter - revolutionary activities, including moderate protests and critical writings, the risk of arrest.
The anti - government graffiti and speeches are considered serious crimes.
Cuba has a community of bloggers, led by the popular commentator Yoani Sánchez, who often writes about how she and her husband are followed and harassed by government agents.
Sánchez has made several requests to leave the country to receive awards, but the authorities have always been denied.
The arrest of an American citizen may increase tensions between the communist government of the Castro brothers in Cuba and the Obama administration, which is a " slow " to improve relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported by the New York Times on Friday night.
The new American policy stresses that if the Cuban government takes concrete steps, such as the release of political prisoners and to create more space for the opposition, there will be reciprocity of part of the United States.
Mobile phones and laptops are legal in Cuba, even though they are new and coveted products in a country where the average salary of a government worker is $15 per month.
The Cuban government granted to ordinary citizens the right to buy mobile Only this year; they are used mainly for text messages, since a 15 - minute telephone conversation would cost the daily wage.
The use of the Internet is extremely limited in the island.
It is available in expensive hotels and for foreign visitors in the country, as well as some government buildings, such as universities.
Cubans who want to connect, often have to give their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
The arrest of an American in Cuba is rare.
Most of the few U. S. prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug trafficking, said Gloria Berbena, S. Interests representation in Havana.
Berbena said that he could not provide more information on the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that, in any other open society would be as mobile free, in Cuba is a crime said Jose Miguel Vivanco, director of the Americas group Human Rights Watch, which recently published a harsh report on freedoms in Cuba, called " new Castro, Cuba ", referring to the installation of Raul Castro as leader of the country, to replace his older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said that the defendants are often arrested, tried and imprisoned in a day.
He said that any solution would probably be political and that the Cuban government often causes a negative reaction in the United States, at a time when the two countries are beginning to have more dialogue.
