On Saturday, the Pakistani authorities to the alleged mastermind of a plot to send five men of Northern Virginia to Afghanistan in order to kill American troops, saying that they hoped that this case could help an extensive network of terrorist recruiters, the Internet in search of young men radicalized.
Investigators said they were chasing a mysterious insurgent figure, known as Saifullah, who invited the men to Pakistan after discovering that one of them made comments approving terrorist attacks on the Internet video site YouTube.
Arrived in Pakistan, these men were guided by Saifullah who tried to help them to reach the remote area in the tribal belt of Pakistan, which is home of Al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a representative of the Pakistani intelligence official who had been briefed on the case said on Saturday that Saifullah was unable to convince the commanders of Al Qaeda that the men were not part of a plot by the CIA to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they were isolated for several days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the mountains of the northwest, which have become a terrorist haven
They were seen as part of a covert operation.
That is why they were rejected, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the case.
The official said that the men were not inmutaron and even were trying to get the proper approval for access to the camps of Al Qaeda, when they were arrested by the Pakistani law enforcement authorities.
The case of the five men, who remain in Pakistan and who are interviewed by the FBI underlines the critical role of recruiters in the identification of potential terrorists and perhaps more important, in the determination of the people who trust.
Since the attacks of September 11, 2001, the U. S. secret services has made it a priority to try to infiltrate people within Al Qaeda.
The Recruiters of the organization play the role of firewalls, refusing entry to those who do not show a serious commitment and those who might be spies.
According to analysts, the American recruits are studied closely by al-Qaeda.
But they are also very attractive for the group because of their potential access to American targets and their value propagandaire.
But, senior analyst for the NEFA Foundation, based in the United States, said that the terrorist groups also have become much more cautious in recent years with regard to those who admit, because the American intelligence services have become experts in their recruitment methods.
