The data from a test reveal persistent racial differences
The federal report last week on the results in mathematics has brought good news for public schools in Washington D. C.
Although the district is still far behind the schools in the country, the report shows that the Grade 4 and Grade 5 (cm1 - cm2) are much greater progress in the past two years in cities such as Atlanta, Chicago and New York
But what in the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (National Assessment of Educational progress) is the persistent gap between African - American and white students, both at local and national level.
The average scores of white students in fourth Grade of D. C. over the past two years, grew from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500) , but their peers African - Americans rose by only three points, 209 to 212.
The achievement gap has actually increased between 2007 and 2009, from 53 to 58 points.
The progress of African - Americans in Grade 8 (4th) generally remained essentially fixed, falling just one point from 245 to 244.
The average score of whites were not included in the results of the test, because the sample size was not large enough.
The overview over a period of six years is not more encouraging.
In 2003, the gap between blacks and whites in Grade 4 () , when the first Enpe in the district, was 60 points (262 to 202) .
Although the results achieved by children in both groups have increased during this period, the difference has been reduced to 58 points.
Last week, some advocates in the District have expressed concern that the rising celebrated by the Director of education institutions Michelle A. Rhee and Mayor Adrian M. Fenty (Democrat) were powered by white students, who are already good elements.
This would suggest that we have improved the whole to those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and embarrassing, said Jeff Smith, director of D. C. Voice, a non - profit group that advocates for equality in education in the District.
I do not move for a span of two or three points, said the Council member of the D. C., Kwame R. Brown (accumulation) , who has a daughter in the fourth class of Eaton primary school) .
Brown, a frequent critic of the management style of Rhee, said that the message of the results is that the middle schools (colleges) of the city desperately need attention.
Really, you always want to see the positive signs, and I respect that.
But the concern is that we do not spend enough time and energy to our middle schools.
Rhee said that the District should continue to find better ways to meet the needs of students in difficulty.
This autumn, for example, some teachers have been trained to use a new curriculum of reading, the Wilson reading system, aimed at pupils in the upper classes of the elementary school and middle school, which dominated the fundamentals of reading earlier in their school career and the significantly behind their peers.
The mathematics of every day, a mathematics curriculum from kindergarten to sixth grade, which emphasizes games and experiences in real life, which was introduced in the district under the former superintendent Clifford Janey, which by the some of the progress reported last week.
I believe that we must continue to work to offer the best speeches to students who are below the level of degree, said Rhee.
Others say that the results of the NAEP raise the question of whether Rhee can continue to raise the overall results of the system and will provide the extra money and resources for schools with less success in order to reduce the gap.
This is a dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a professor of education at the University of California at Berkeley, tests of cities.
The conventional political solution is to spend your resources and management reforms to schools located in the poorest neighborhoods of Washington.
Then the objective can Also have political repercussions that this important program.
But the problem, of course, is that, like other schools, it is clinging to the middle class white and black.
Our focus is to ensure that we build a system of excellent schools.
We need to strengthen our schools, so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive an excellent public education.
Janey, now superintendent of schools in Newark, said in an interview this week that one of the essential element to reduce the difference in performance is the year of traditional public school, currently 180 days in the District of Washington, to compete with charter schools.
We must reach nearly 200 days to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with the union of their teachers last year for 185 days, which it considers a " starting point " to increase in the next contract.
