USA: a panel of sarcophagus that belonged to Zola awarded $1.5 million
A panel of Roman sarcophagus that belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was sold on Thursday at $1.5 million, well above the estimated price, announced the art dealer Sotheby's.
This panel of 2 metres long by 63 cm high, dates from the third century after Christ, and its price was estimated between 150,000 and 250,000 dollars.
The marble " representing four scenes in a sophisticated architectural decor, surrounded by sátiros and women, is a rare piece, there are only four or five in the world, " said Florent Heintz, Vice - President of the auction of art of ancient Rome and Egypt at Sotheby's.
It was sold between a hundred lots.
The sale is still continues, but this batch is certainly what the buyer, until now, most of it, " says the AFP a spokesman of Sotheby's, Dan Abernethy.
The discovery of the acquisition of marble by Emile Zola back in a few days.
The panel was almost 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the family, then appeared in the home of the French actress Cécile Sorel, as an element of their bathtub in her hotel particular, and Paul Reynaud, in the Third French Republic and President of the Council of ministers, before the accession to power of Marshal Pétain.
For fifty years, their fate was uncertain.
Reviewing the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz discovered that this panel was part of a " succession Emile Zola " opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of " Thérèse Raquin " and the " Rougon - Macquart ".
