The Turkish justice dissolved the pro - Kurdish party, a decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled Friday the dissolution of the main pro - Kurdish party in the country, a decision that immediately provoked anger in the Kurdish community, in the south - east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a " hotbed of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity, " declared to the press, the president of the Court, Hasim Kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, with a majority of seven votes needed to get the dissolution, indicated Kiliç, and added that 37 of the leaders of the party, including its President Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for five years.
Furthermore, The judge announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity which enjoyed Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the assets of the party by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (550) .
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that Members of Parliament before being parliamentarians without partisan label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, which accused the DTP to the " principles " of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) , considered a terrorist organisation by Ankara and many other countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party, " no connection " to have the PKK, but refuses to describe it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with him.
The verdict of the court comes as the government is to reach out to the Kurdish community in proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights, for which the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and put an end to the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP claimed that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in the southeast, where many demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan, degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of demonstrators gathered in front of the premises of the DTP in Diyarbakir, the largest city in southeast populated mostly by Kurds.
The police fired tear gas grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails and stones with slingshots.
Hundreds of people marched in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the decision of Justice would " deepen the despair ".
Turkey cannot solve this issue (Kurdish, banning a party, " he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve anything, " said the Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a frustrating the democratic opening launched by the government, commented on the political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, " he added.
On Thursday, the PKK has claimed an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in the north of Turkey, one of the most deadly in recent months.
New Silicon Valley
For many years it was considered as a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenogrado, one of the 10 districts of Moscow, was in the Soviet Union, a place of secret weapons, under strict supervision.
Today, the community with its 216 000 inhabitants, 37 kilometres from the centre of Moscow, is regarded as the " Silicon Valley ".
Here are important centres of research and production of micro and nanoelectronics.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenogrado have contacted the seat of scientific Riedberg in Frankfurt, with the university institutes and companies in the centre of innovation in Frankfurt (FIZ) .
There were signed several mutual visits and now, on Wednesday, and Riedberg in Frankfurt a " protocol of close collaboration ".
The signatories were the Deputy mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the Selengrado, Anatoly Smirnov, led the Russian delegation, Frankfurt the head of planning services.
In 2010 will be representatives of the FIZ and small and medium - sized enterprises In the scientific research, for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
It is a continuous scientific exchange.
But it is also about economic relations.
Firms of the FIZ will be on the growing Russian market.
Conversely, want to Russian science firms contracts in Germany.
Selenogrado is the seat of major Russian research institutes and companies.
These include, for example, the Moscow Institute of electronic technology, the big corporations Sitronics and Rosssijskaja - Elektronika.
The community was founded in 1958 as the so - called " socialist planned city " for research.
Selenogrado (literally translated as " green City ") received its name from the forested hills landscape, in which the are embedded.
Stuttgart
The dimension of Stuttgart 21 can start not high enough.
For the proponents of the project is purely and simply " the new heart of Europe ".
The law so. S21 is much more than the reduction of a railway station, more than a monstrous construction project, which the City of the capital of Baden - württemberga a decade of chaos of construction sites.
Stuttgart 21 is born of the spirit of the 1980s.
With terminals, which end up in the middle of the city, were at that time as the relics of the 19th century, acting as brakes of a modern rail traffic, since it was formerly took a lot of time to get the back to the front.
In short, drive - to go further.
And That is why the head stations disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: a station of trains, which is about halfway on the trans - European rail between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava where the slogan of " heart of Europe ".
The project S21 will really start, although the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners have recognized that the cost to bury the station in the capitals of Hesse and Bavaria, was exorbitant.
Head stations have no entry and exit problem any more, however, since there are modern reversible with cars at both ends.
However, Stuttgart 21 and the new route after Ulm is now being addressed.
Regional and local politicians have.
The train continues, because the risks of the great individual infrastructure projects of the Einzelprojekts the Republic of taxpayers and not the state company.
From the point of view, the project is relatively well justified.
It creates new urban area, which, according to the computergenerierten graphs of the planners generated by computer - will be very green.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
The station and the road are designed for the transport of persons, which was attributed to the huge growth typical of the 1980s.
At that time was not yet the competition from low - cost flights.
But The modern transport policy must first deal to strengthen the transport of goods, as the transport by rail is much more environmentally friendly than by lorries on the roads.
But the new route, with its inclinations, unsuitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious indirectly affects many other rail projects.
For example, six billion euros will be in the Schwäbischen are buried.
This is the official figure.
Experts believe that ten to 15 billion is more realistic.
One thing is certain, in the next decade will lack the money for other crossings and congestion in the network.
The list of the Ministry of transport in 60 major projects.
One of the most important is the expansion of the section through the Rhine Valley of 180 kilometres.
Since 1987, is being built on the route in slow motion.
It would be really urgent to support here on the fungus.
But the project S21 will act as a brake.
The stretch of the Rhine Valley will be the bottleneck for international freight traffic, and this in the heart of Europe.
