The poker of Manuel Vincent
Manuel Vicent presented in " poker Asse " (Alfaguara, illustrations of Fernando Vicente) thirty X - rays of writers who have crossed his literary life (and, in some cases, his other life) .
It does not gender predictable and apprehended (biographical profiles, life and work) , but looking for something similar to the core of ignition of the character creator.
The trip is exciting and Vincent saves scares or the illuminations.
In addition to an exquisite pleasure, this book is also a moving invitation to readings and relecturas.
Here I leave you a few snapshots.
On Albert Camus: " in its pages, I discovered that the Mediterranean was not a sea, but a spiritual, almost physical, the same as I felt without name: the pleasure against the sad fate, the morality without guilt and innocence without any God. "
On Samuel Beckett: " nihilistic, Christian, he wrote what he had in the blood, not in the head, between powerlessness and ignorance, with a dazzling poetic humour, pointless, as the blade of the knife that was about to kill him. "
On Graham Greene: " Our man was inspired by this woman with a passion that lasted 13 years, in whose meat the emotion of adultery with the pleasure of remorse, a spiritual privilege which was to reach the sky On the road to perdition. "
On James Joyce: " the Ulysses was published in Paris in 1922 by Sylvia Beach. It is one of the tops of eight thousand metres of world literature, he must climb by the north face, on the wall, from which it again and again the best. "
On William Faulkner: " It was a strange type.
In itself, he said that it was the heir of a landowner in the county and other times he was the son of a black and a crocodile.
Both dreams of greatness. "
On Louis - Ferdinand Céline: " This writer took the cry pushed from a bridge by the personality of Munch to carry its response to the bottom of the night of the 20th century, in his literary form, and did so in a trip fleeing itself and invoking posterity with a violent speech to the worms. "
On Dorothy Parker: " One day brought to its knees and prayed: " God, I beg you to do that I write as a woman. "
On Joseph Conrad: " on his tomb were engraved to Spenser: " sleep after the effort,/after the storm the port,/the rest after the war,/after life extremely pleased death. "
On Virginia Wolf: " in her luggage, she had always their depression.
