Brazil sets a date for the departure of Zelaya
The Brazilian government has set a deadline for the residence of Manuel Zelaya in its embassy in Tegucigalpa.
The deposed president must leave the diplomatic legation no later than 27 January 2010, when his term officially end.
Francisco Catunda, chargé d'affaires of the Brazilian embassy in the Honduran capital, confirmed to TV Globo that " Mel " knows that he must leave before that date of the embassy, where he has refugee from 21 September.
" He is aware that he must go on 27 January, at the end of his mandate, it must seek another destination. "
The station also quoted the former agent, who confirmed his intention to leave the embassy before the deadline: " My position is to leave as soon as possible, with the support of the government of Brazil, " Zelaya said by telephone.
After the elections on 29 November (during which Porfirio Lobo was elected) , Zelaya assured that he would remain in the Brazilian embassy until January.
However, the same week, he tried to seek refuge in Brazil.
The operation was finally failed, since Zelaya refused the status of exiled political intended to impose the de facto government headed by Roberto Micheletti.
Thank you very much
After days roses since last spring, during which the inflation of assets has been the dominant note on the markets, the uncertainty there arises again, which is not surprising since it is their natural state, in an environment in which the players take decisions on the future inherently uncertain.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilize the markets was to monetize debt by the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by providing liquidity at rates close to zero, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilize.
The Central banks have already confirmed that the direct purchases of assets have virtually ended and, without questioning their heterodox policy of liquidity, begin to put some sand in the wheels, as did the ECB with its next week.
Therefore, investors have doubts about the ability of the global economy to an economic recovery without heterodox measures and we are witnessing a reversal of the reduction of risk premiums.
The volatility of the stock markets and the spreads on corporate bonds have rise again, although still a long way from the levels they achieved at the beginning of the year.
The States were forced to socialize the risk private and public debt is affected.
There is a flight to quality and the United States, Japan and Germany have been the refuge chosen by investors, leading to an extension of the differences between the countries in the euro zone in regard to Germany.
Spain has been barely affected by this episode of instability, but then came Standard& Poor's and threatened with a new downward revision of the qualification of the Kingdom of Spain.
On the other hand, a bit of uncertainty is not bad to silence the defenders of the moral hazard, who tried to provoke a case of conscience in global economic policy that had stalled the destructive effects of the credit on the destruction of employment, when what we should do is declare a new day of Thanksgiving.
However, the situation of Dubai resembles a tribal fight between the sheiks to restore the power in the Emirates and we have already seen the case of Greece.
A government that conceals a public deficit, elections and a new government, which is in the same direction.
Prodi did in Italy after Berlusconi and Socrates in Portugal after Durão Barroso.
It makes no sense that Ecofin Hungary at the beginning of the saves a breach of its external payments of the year and allow a member country of the euro area not to meet its commitments.
What makes sense is that the Ecofin has forced the Greek government to be transparent and its citizens of the need for extraordinary measures to maintain the stability of its public finances.
If, as we hope, we are faced with an episode of normalization of risk premiums, after some excesses in leveraged positions, would be within the Erwarteten.
In the case of Spain, as long as our differences of public debt increase to the obligations of European corporate should not worry.
If the European and continued to increase, it would be a special Spanish risk.
The Standard& Poor's is an anecdote. When our indicators are forcing the majority of services to anticipate their recovery and to revise upwards their forecasts for 2011, including the OECD and the European Commission, to return to the burden with a Japanese scenario for the Spanish economy, it does not much hope for their warning.
Again, this has to be an excellent opportunity to buy assets in Spain, although for the moment " caution ".
Related sectors
The chairman of Iberdrola, Ignacio Sánchez Galán, was the first to speak yesterday before the subcommittee of the Congress of Deputies in the discussion these days the energy strategy of Spain in the next two decades.
After his speech, which was followed by the chairman of gas Natural - Fenosa, Rafael Villaseca, gave the press a few key points about what he had submitted to the subcommittee behind closed doors.
For the chairman of Iberdrola, Spain needs to invest 50 billion euros by 2020 and other 60 billion between that date and 2030, where nuclear power plants in operation today would remain open.
If this is not the case, the necessary investments will not be $60 billion, but up to 95 billion.
However, Iberdrola believes that in the next decade, investments should not be used to increase the production capacity, but in distribution networks and international groupings.
From 2020, the issue is changing, and it will increase the power.
His proposal focuses on both gas and coal plants with mechanisms for recovery of carbon dioxide and, above all, on renewable energy.
In this case, it believes that 18,000 MW of more are needed, with other " energies of support. "
Galán, who believes that the draft law of sustainable economy that has just been adopted by the government is in line with what his company, did not want to attack the royal decree aimed to encourage the use of coal, which contradicts policies to combat climate change.
In his opinion, there is " a clear commitment to the long - term " in this sense, despite the measures, as the chairman of Iberdrola.
Be that as it may, believes that investment decisions, although they are in the long term, it must begin to taken, because they take some time and a stable remuneration framework is needed to address them.
